<TITLE> Floods in full fury </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, August 1 (bdnews24.com)  The flooding continued to take a turn for the worse in saturated parts of the country as tens of thousands of people were struggling to fight the deluge amid slow relief efforts. At least 14 rivers were flowing above flood levels at 24 points Wednesday, according to an official flood forecaster. The situation worsened Wednesday after 11 rivers had flowed above the danger mark Tuesday. Media reports said Wednesday that the relief workers were sluggish to reach supplies to the battered region. Md Ariful Islam, assistant engineer of the Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre, said the flow of waters in rivers along the Brahmaputra-Jamuna basin remained almost unchanged Wednesday. But the rivers in the Ganges and the Meghna basins continued to rage Wednesday. The flood bulletin said Wednesday the river Dharala at Kurigram point receded 3 cm but was still flowing 51 cm above the danger mark. The Brahmaputra at Nunkhaoa and Chilmari points receded 6cm and 4cm. But waters in the two points were flowing 50 cm and 71 cm above the flood level. The Jamuna was flowing 83 cm, 117 cm and 122 cm above danger marks at Bahadurabad, Sirajganj and Aricha points. The Kaliganga at Taraghat and the Dhaleswari at Rikabi Bazar points were flowing 92cm and 50cm above flood level. The Padma in Goalanda and Bhagyakul swelled 14cm and 14cm and was flowing 136cm and 92cm above danger marks. The Surma in Kanaighat, the Someswari, the Kushiara and the Kongsha were flowing above the danger levels. In some points waters, however, receded before 6am Wednesday. The Surma began to slow down at Kanaighat and Sunamganj points but swelled at Sylhet point where it flowed 3 cm above danger mark. The waters in Kanaighat, Sylhet and Sunamganj were flowing 131 cm, 42 cm and 60 cm above danger levels. The Someswari at Durgapur and the Kongsha at Jariajanjil were flowing 180 cm and 166 cm above danger levels. The Kushiara was flowing 35 cm above danger marks at Sheola point. bdnew